data: {"type":"response.output_text.delta","content_index":0,"delta":"**","item_id":"msg_034bfeb1d12106f70169e478e72c04819589cd4e178bba1677","logprobs":[],"obfuscation":"LdKxDTfMMi7rZJ","output_index":1,"sequence_number":725}

event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_034bfeb1d12106f70169e478e72c04819589cd4e178bba1677","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":726,"text":"### Monte Hall / Monty Hall 3-door problem (logic explanation)\n\n**Setup**\n- There are **3 doors**.\n- Behind **1 door** is a **prize** (car).\n- Behind the other **2 doors** are **goats**.\n- You pick **1 door** initially.\n- The host (Monty) **knows where the prize is** and then:\n  1. Opens **one of the two remaining doors** that has a **goat**.\n  2. Offers you the choice to **stay** with your original door or **switch** to the other unopened door.\n\n---\n\n## Key logical fact: your initial choice is either right or wrong\nOn the first pick:\n\n### Case A: You initially pick the prize (probability = 1/3)\n- Your door has the car.\n- The host opens a goat among the remaining two.\n- If you **switch**, you move to a goat → you lose.\n\n### Case B: You initially pick a goat (probability = 2/3)\n- Your door is a goat.\n- The host must open a goat door among the remaining two.\n- But since you already picked a goat, the **only way the host can open a goat** without revealing the car is that:\n  - The car must be behind the **other unopened door** after the host opens one goat.\n\nSo in Case B, if you **switch**, you move to the car → you win.\n\n---\n\n## Therefore: switching vs staying\n- **Stay** wins only in Case A → probability **1/3**\n- **Switch** wins in Case B → probability **2/3**\n\n✅ **Switching is twice as likely to win.**\n\n---\n\n## A “probability mass” / bookkeeping view (very direct)\nInitially:\n- Your chosen door has probability **1/3** of car.\n- The other two doors together have probability **2/3** of containing the car.\n\nThe host then **removes one goat door** by opening it (and you’re left with exactly one other unopened door). Importantly:\n- That other unopened door inherits the **entire remaining probability mass** of “car is somewhere among the two unchosen doors,” which was **2/3**.\n- So the unopened other door after the host opens one goat has probability **2/3** of being the car.\n\nThus:\n- **Stay**: 1/3\n- **Switch**: 2/3\n\n---\n\n## What makes the problem non-intuitive\nMany people mistakenly think:\n> “After one door is opened, there are 2 doors left, so it should be 1/2 each.”\n\nThat would be true only if the host opened a random door without using knowledge of where the car is. But here the host’s action is **conditional**:\n- The host **always** opens a goat door.\n- That conditional information shifts probability toward the door you didn’t initially choose.\n\n---\n\n### Final result\n- **Switch:** win probability **2/3**\n- **Stay:** win probability **1/3**"}

